From b2f22a3fdc95dabdd61db22f75cde5b56156fccb Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alex MKX <akm@gfn.team>
Date: Fri, 5 Jun 2026 20:29:10 +0300
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] opencode: forbid general subagent fallback in bootstrap

The 0001 patch routes dispatch templates to @implementer/@code-reviewer
with a soft fallback to general-purpose. In practice models still pick
general because:
  - general is a built-in catch-all with a generous description
  - named subagents in user opencode.json often lack a description, so
    they look weaker in the task tool schema
  - the OR-clause 'otherwise general-purpose' gives the model permission
    to pick general

Add a hard rule to the using-superpowers bootstrap (injected into every
primary-agent session via the opencode plugin's chat.messages.transform
hook) that forbids general/general-purpose when named subagents are
configured. The bootstrap injection means this reaches the model on
every step, overriding the softer OR-clause in skill prompt templates.
---
 skills/using-superpowers/SKILL.md | 26 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 26 insertions(+)

diff --git a/skills/using-superpowers/SKILL.md b/skills/using-superpowers/SKILL.md
index c8a8570..120645d 100644
--- a/skills/using-superpowers/SKILL.md
+++ b/skills/using-superpowers/SKILL.md
@@ -15,6 +15,32 @@ IF A SKILL APPLIES TO YOUR TASK, YOU DO NOT HAVE A CHOICE. YOU MUST USE IT.
 This is not negotiable. This is not optional. You cannot rationalize your way out of this.
 </EXTREMELY-IMPORTANT>
 
+<EXTREMELY-IMPORTANT>
+## Subagent Dispatching (primary agents only)
+
+When you dispatch a subagent via the `task` tool, you MUST pick a named
+subagent type that matches the work:
+
+- `implementer` — write/edit code, run tests, commit
+- `code-reviewer` — review diffs against spec and code quality
+- `explore` — read-only research: find files, grep symbols, where-is-X
+
+**NEVER pass `subagent_type: "general"` or `"general-purpose"`** when any
+of the named subagents above is configured in this OpenCode session.
+The `general` subagent is a generic catch-all that bypasses the
+per-role model configuration the user set up. Falling back to it
+silently wastes their model budget and defeats the whole point of
+named subagents.
+
+If the task doesn't fit any named subagent — split it into pieces that
+do, or do it inline in the primary session. Do NOT route around named
+subagents by picking `general`.
+
+This rule overrides any "if available; otherwise general-purpose"
+soft-fallback wording you see in skill prompt templates. Treat
+`general` as unavailable.
+</EXTREMELY-IMPORTANT>
+
 ## Instruction Priority
 
 Superpowers skills override default system prompt behavior, but **user instructions always take precedence**:
